WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:07.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:21.370
&gt;&gt; Helena Zinkham: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:23.390
I'm Helena -- yes, good afternoon.

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:26.690
[laughter] Wake ourselves
after lunch a little bit.

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:31.190
I'm Helena Zinkham, director
for Collections and Services,

00:00:31.190 --> 00:00:34.100
as well as chief of the Prints
and Photographs Division here

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:35.710
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:38.580
And it's my genuine pleasure
this afternoon to welcome you

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:46.010
to a special program featuring
Bob Adelman and Ira Glasser.

00:00:46.010 --> 00:00:50.690
They're going to talk about
their book "Visions of Liberty."

00:00:50.690 --> 00:00:53.730
The subject matter is actually
quite serious, isn't it?

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:56.960
Human right, civil
rights, civil liberties.

00:00:56.960 --> 00:01:03.410
But these are two imminent,
life-long advocates for justice,

00:01:03.410 --> 00:01:06.840
who happen to be quite
lively speakers as well.

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:10.240
So this topic is going to come
alive for us this afternoon.

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:17.530 position:56%
Back in 1991, when Bob and Ira --
documentary photographer Bob Adelman

00:01:17.530 --> 00:01:20.560
and American Civil Liberties
Union president Ira Glasser,

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:24.220
they teamed up for a book
called "Visions of Liberty,"

00:01:24.220 --> 00:01:29.340
honoring the 200th anniversary
of the American Bill of Rights.

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:32.870
Now almost 25 years later,
I'm looking forward to hearing

00:01:32.870 --> 00:01:36.330
if you think we've made progress
or not, but we're also here

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:40.210
to celebrate the 800th
anniversary of the Magna Carta

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:44.610
and the 50th anniversary
of the Civil Rights Act.

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:47.500
That's a lot of anniversaries
colliding, isn't it?

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:49.790
Piling up.

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:54.170
And they too will help us both
appreciate the achievements

00:01:54.170 --> 00:01:56.420
and how much further down
the road we have to go

00:01:56.420 --> 00:02:01.790
to actually reach social justice.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:04.840
To introduce you in a more
formal way to our speakers,

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:08.330
you have wonderful biographies in
your program, so I am just going

00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:12.920 position:56%
to mention briefly, on behalf of the
videotape, that Bob Adelman is one

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:16.750
of the foremost photographers
of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:21.400
Born in New York City in 1930,
he grew up on Long Island

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:24.810
and has degrees from Rutgers,
Harvard, and Columbia.

00:02:24.810 --> 00:02:29.190
He studied photography with Alexi
Brodovitch, the famed art director

00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:31.260
of Harper's Bazaar Magazine.

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:36.380 position:56%
With an avid interest in social and
political events of the early 1960s,

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:39.400
Bob was drawn to the sit-ins
staged by young students

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:41.360
across the American south.

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:45.540
He volunteered to take photos of
the demonstrations for the Congress

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:49.370
of Racial Equality, CORE, and
has continued to be involved

00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:53.480
with Civil Rights issues and
the human condition ever since.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:57.300
In 2014, Bob was invited to
serve at the Library of Congress

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.270
as a consulting photographer,
to expand awareness

00:03:00.270 --> 00:03:01.670
of our visual collections.

00:03:01.670 --> 00:03:05.510
Thank you for that.

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:09.630
[ Applause ]

00:03:09.630 --> 00:03:14.380 position:56%
Ira Glasser served with the American
Civil Liberties Union for 34 years,

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:21.380
executive director
from 1978 until 2001.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:22.840
Glasser has published widely

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:25.490
on civil liberty principles,
as well as issues.

00:03:25.490 --> 00:03:28.610
His writings have appeared in the
New York Times, Washington Post,

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:33.170
Village Voice, Harper's, New
Republic Nation, Christianity,

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:36.430
and Crisis, along many others.

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.320
He's also been a frequent
guest and debater on such radio

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:43.700
and television shows as William
F. Buckley's Firing Line.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:48.140 position:56%
Born and raised in New York, Glasser
achieved a bachelors in mathematics

00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:51.490
from Queens College and
a masters in mathematics

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:53.660
from Ohio State University.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:59.610
A few words of thanks,
first to the Prints

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:02.180
and Photographs Division
staff, the Law Library staff,

00:04:02.180 --> 00:04:07.040 position:56%
and the Interpretive Programs Office
staff, who collaborated seamlessly

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:09.060
to bring a lot of disparate
parts together

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:11.410
for our program this afternoon.

00:04:11.410 --> 00:04:14.800
To see more of their talented
work, please be sure to take a look

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:19.610
at the very popular Law
Library blog, In Custodia Legis.

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:23.200
The valuable Vision Materials
blog, called Picture This.

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:25.990
And of course, the Civil
Rights Act exhibition,

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:27.990
which is up in the
Jefferson Building all the way

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:29.450
through January.

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:34.560
I also want to acknowledge
Roberta Shaffer.

00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:37.000
Are you here today?

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.420
There you go.

00:04:38.420 --> 00:04:39.930
[laughter].

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:42.920
So quiet in the middle.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:47.990
Roberta, our inspirational
leader, a library leader.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:52.340
Former law librarian, associate
librarian for Library Services.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:57.950
But most importantly today, the
personal sponsor for this project.

00:04:57.950 --> 00:05:01.510 position:56%
Mr. Adelman's consultancy and
photography at the library is funded

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:05.550
through Roberta, a
self-described futurist.

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:08.200
And here's one thing
I admire a great deal.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:09.840
Roberta, you see connections

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:13.260
that build a stronger future
direction for all of us.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:15.350
I don't think I ever would
have thought of the potential

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:20.220
for combining well-reasoned law
with the artistry of photography,

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:22.360
and yet you knew how
to make it happen

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.790
so that there are creative
agents together

00:05:24.790 --> 00:05:29.520
to make sure the world
changes and grows better.

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:30.820
Robert -- [applause].

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:37.640
Great, thank you.

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:40.530
So we almost called this
the Program of the Roberts.

00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:42.900
We have our sponsor, Roberta.

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.680
Our wonderful chief of
staff, Robert Newlen.

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:48.760
Bob. Would you like a new
middle name today, Ira?

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:50.320
[laughter]

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.010
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: You're outnumbered.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:54.650 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Helena Zinkham: So more seriously
then, our wonderful chief of staff,

00:05:54.650 --> 00:05:59.880
Robert Newlen, formerly associate
law librarian and mastermind

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.440
for the Magna Carta exhibition.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:05.290
You're going to tap your three
worlds of expertise, law, art,

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:08.770
history, as a great moderator
for our program today.

00:06:08.770 --> 00:06:10.570
Thank you.

