00:06:47.490 --> 00:06:52.420
And I would also like to
acknowledge Roberta Shaffer

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:55.840
and making programs
like this possible.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:00.190 position:56%
And Roberta, we owe you a great deal
and are just very grateful for all

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:04.280
that you have and are doing
for the Library of Congress.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:07.180
With that said, it's a little
intimidating to be sitting

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:12.470
with two extremely iconic gentlemen
in the areas of civil liberties

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:15.800
and social justice, but here I am.

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:20.010
And here's how I propose
that we spend the next hour,

00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:22.370
or whatever we have left now.

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:26.570
We're going to start off talking
a little bit about how this,

00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:29.950
my dog-eared copy of "Visions
of Liberty: The Bill of Rights

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:33.160
for All Americans," came about.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:38.630
And then we're going to move to
Bob's photographs in several areas.

00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:44.780
And it's really Sophie's choice,
trying to choose photographs

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:46.380
that we want to talk about today,

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:49.960
but thanks to Verna
Curtis, we have done that.

00:07:49.960 --> 00:07:54.420
And so gentlemen, I'm going to
open the question to you now.

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:56.970
How did this book come about?

00:07:56.970 --> 00:07:59.870
How did this collaboration start?

00:07:59.870 --> 00:08:01.170
And spare no details.

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:06.830
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: Well, he goes
like this, but it was his idea.

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:10.810
[laughter] And those of you
who may not know him know

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:14.550
that he is pathologically
stubborn about his ideas.

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:22.640
And he proposed this book to
me many times over many years,

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:25.910
and each time he did, I
told him it was impossible.

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:27.880
I couldn't do it, I
couldn't work with him.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:31.850
I already had a job as the
ACLU executive director

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:39.020
that occupied me 95 hours a
week, and what spare time I had,

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:42.810
I was trying to reserve for
my children so that they could

00:08:42.810 --> 00:08:45.100
at least remember who I was.

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:51.070 position:56%
And he acknowledged that, a man of
great feeling, and then said, "Yeah,

00:08:51.070 --> 00:08:52.850
but it's a really important book.

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:54.150
We really should do it.

00:08:54.150 --> 00:08:55.450
There isn't a book like it."

00:08:55.450 --> 00:08:57.490
This went on, and on,
and on, and on.

00:08:57.490 --> 00:09:00.930
And I kept successfully
resisting it.

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:04.700
Then it got to be close to 1991 and
the 200th anniversary, and he said,

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:07.220
"This is really a compelling
time to do it."

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:09.250
And I resisted it again.

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:10.600 position:56%
It was impossible, I couldn't do it.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:13.590 position:56%
So he said, "Well, maybe we can get"
-- you know, it was really supposed

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:18.660
to be a book of photographs
with captions

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:21.330
or maybe a paragraph caption.

00:09:21.330 --> 00:09:28.000
And so he said, "Well, maybe we can
get somebody to write the captions

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.900
and to write the paragraphs,"
and we thought of a few people.

00:09:30.900 --> 00:09:33.450
And I asked Kurt Vonnegut
if he would do it,

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:36.050 position:56%
because he was a big ACLU supporter.

00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:37.650
And he said, "No, you should do it.

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:39.720
I don't know enough about this."

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:41.780
And this went on, and on, and on.

00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:43.170
We couldn't find anybody to do it.

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:48.380
And finally, I don't remember
how, I agreed to do it.

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:50.810
And then somewhere along the
way, because as you can tell,

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:56.290
even by my story now, I'm
not a man of few words,

00:09:56.290 --> 00:09:59.880
what happened is it turned out
from being a book of photographs

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:05.500
with captions to being a
book of text with photos.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.140
And then Bob basically
produced the book

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:14.020
with Richard Seaver
of Arcade Publishing.

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:18.870
And I must say, I'm glad I gave it.

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:23.610
And having the opportunity
to sort of put

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:29.620
on paper what I had been talking
about to countless audiences

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:35.960 position:56%
and trying to explain the importance
and origins of our basic values

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:40.320
of liberty in this country,
and having it accompanied

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:47.580
by the really glittering array
of photographs that we were able

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:51.500
to assemble, most of which
were Bob, and the others

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:55.240
that weren't his were ones
that he found and selected,

00:10:55.240 --> 00:11:01.990
was a great privilege and a great
joy, and I still love to leaf

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:03.920
through all those pictures.

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:09.370
And they illustrate
things that words can't,

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:14.250
and that has been Bob's
great genius, in my view,

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:17.170
in tracking so many
movements of social justice

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:19.500
in this country as he has.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:23.720
So you have a right to reply,
if you have a different view,

00:11:23.720 --> 00:11:26.370
but that was how I [inaudible].

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:38.880
&gt;&gt; Well, I think the -- I think one
thing that we should all be aware

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:47.320
of is that, at the
time, if you remember,

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:51.480
it was a very vivid
political process

00:11:51.480 --> 00:12:00.470
that the Constitution was
celebrated, the 200th anniversary

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:03.580
of the Constitution was celebrated.

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:07.940
And Ira reminded me, it
was not the Bill of Rights

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:12.700
that was being celebrated,
but the Constitution itself.

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:18.160
And when we published this book,

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:24.980
there was very little public
acclaim for the Bill of Rights.

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:33.030
Now, the reason I was always
so persistent in getting

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:39.410 position:56%
after Ira was because, first of all,
I didn't know anybody who knew more

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:46.970
about the Bill of Rights and had
more penetrative things to say.

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:55.590
But I envisioned somehow
photographing all these landmark

00:12:55.590 --> 00:13:05.000
decisions and, you know, all the
social processes that led up to it.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.540
As it turned out, once
I got into it,

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:12.670
it was extremely difficult
to photograph.

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:17.950 position:56%
For instance, I wanted to photograph
the tension of an immigrant

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:23.380 position:56%
or something, and getting permission
to go to Miami at that time,

00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:28.570 position:56%
where they were retaining a lot of
Cubans, it was virtually impossible.

00:13:28.570 --> 00:13:31.370
I couldn't get in, you know.

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:37.170
So it was really very unfortunate.

00:13:37.170 --> 00:13:43.520
Yet my experiences are
that, for most Americans,

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:48.450
the Bill of Rights is what
it means to be an American.

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:56.190
And as Ira brilliantly points
out in the book, it is the place

00:13:56.190 --> 00:14:01.310
that individuals interact
with government,

00:14:01.310 --> 00:14:07.930
and it's extraordinary individuals
who've won for us our freedom,

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:11.680
our growing freedoms,
or contracting,

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:13.920
depending on what the moment is.

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:20.820
And so I'm glad we got the
book done, but I was very,

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:27.590 position:56%
very frustrated in trying to do the
book, in terms of finding photogenic

00:14:27.590 --> 00:14:30.400
and photographic opportunities.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:37.320
But the thing that someone
just mentioned to me,

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:43.310
that a Russian woman,
who is a journalist,

00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:47.150
has come to America just
to have her child here.

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:49.050
She will return to Russia.

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:53.550
But she wants her child
to be an American citizen

00:14:53.550 --> 00:15:02.680 position:56%
so that he will be assured a freedom
if worst things happen in Russia,

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:07.330
and that's just something
to think about.

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:11.050
Imagine bringing another -- I
mean, she's not the only person.

00:15:11.050 --> 00:15:15.100
Apparently it's a very
real phenomenon,

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:23.190
that to enjoy the benefits that we
have as Americans is so precious

00:15:23.190 --> 00:15:28.700
that a woman would really
risk her lie traveling here,

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:33.580
just to make sure her son, or
child, or daughter was free.

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:34.880
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Terrific.

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:37.530
I'm going to save the
Magna Carta question,

00:15:37.530 --> 00:15:39.770
because I think you've
given such a great segway

00:15:39.770 --> 00:15:42.460 position:56%
to begin looking at the photographs.

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:45.320
So Verna?

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:46.890
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: Were you
going to comment on --

00:15:46.890 --> 00:15:48.660
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Yeah,
we'll come back.

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:49.960
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: Later.

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:52.060
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Verna, can we
take a look at the first group?

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:56.780
And this first group of photographs
we're going to look at are all

00:15:56.780 --> 00:15:59.860
about Martin Luther King.

00:16:03.730 --> 00:16:08.320
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: That's
during the Selma march.

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:10.020
He was having foot trouble.

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:17.120
And in fact, he didn't march a
couple of days because of it.

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:23.150
And I particularly
like this picture,

00:16:23.150 --> 00:16:28.080
because he looks sort of militant.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:33.360
You know, when I first saw this
statue here, I didn't really

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:37.460
like it, because I always
thought he reached out to people,

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:41.770
but this statue here,
he's closed in.

00:16:41.770 --> 00:16:46.810
But really, underneath all
that, he was very determined.

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:52.120
But in addition to that,
he was a master tactician.

00:16:52.120 --> 00:16:57.370
You know, I think of the
Civil Rights Movement

00:16:57.370 --> 00:17:01.770
as the last battles
of the Civil War.

00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:09.420
And compared to the Civil
War, in which hundreds of --

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:17.110
I think 600 or 700,000 people
were killed in the war that,

00:17:17.110 --> 00:17:23.310
in these last battles of the
civil rights, waged in major part

00:17:23.310 --> 00:17:25.770
under Dr. King's direction.

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:28.120
There were very few casualties.

00:17:28.120 --> 00:17:30.290
We all believed in non-violence.

00:17:30.290 --> 00:17:36.370
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Ira, what kind
of thoughts come to your mind

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:40.320
as we're looking at
Bob's photographs now?

00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:42.620
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: How
much younger I was.

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:48.680
[laughter] I mean, I
grew up in New York,

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:56.310
and with that white liberal
illusion that many of us had,

00:17:56.310 --> 00:17:59.290
that racism was a southern
phenomenon,

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:03.110
and all of this stuff was
going on in the south.

00:18:03.110 --> 00:18:08.800
And the first big demonstration
I ever went

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:11.650
to was the March on
Washington in 1963.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:20.340
And I was only 25 then, and I
was not yet working at the ACLU.

00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:29.390
And the feeling of people, black
and white, marching together

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:35.530 position:56%
in those numbers for what they were
marching for at that particular time

00:18:35.530 --> 00:18:41.550
in your history was a
feeling that sort of can't --

00:18:41.550 --> 00:18:45.050
it can be remembered, but
it can't be recaptured.

00:18:45.050 --> 00:18:49.220
And it's something that if I talk
about to my grandchildren, who,

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:56.990
as they come of age, and this to
them is history, what that meant

00:18:56.990 --> 00:19:02.620
at the time, what these
photographs document,

00:19:02.620 --> 00:19:09.950
was a participatory feeling
of turbulence, and change,

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:18.570
and great things underway that
it was difficult to describe.

00:19:18.570 --> 00:19:25.550
And these photographs, I don't
know if the slides include one,

00:19:25.550 --> 00:19:31.950 position:56%
but the ones particularly that Bob
did of the firehouses in Birmingham,

00:19:31.950 --> 00:19:35.830
I remember what it felt
like to first see those

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:38.670
in the early '60s, there.

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:44.470
And that -- you know, I
remember thinking it reminded me

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:45.770
of an El Greco painting.

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:50.550
It was not just an
extraordinary documentation

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:53.820 position:56%
of an extraordinary social struggle,

00:19:53.820 --> 00:19:59.660
but the art of those
photographs was just incredible.

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:05.040 position:56%
And I remember asking Bob for a
copy of this, which I had on my wall

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:07.040
in my apartment in New York
as my kids were growing up.

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:11.350
And every time they would
go back from the kitchen

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:14.220
to their bedroom, they
would see that.

00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:16.850
And sooner or later, they
would ask me, "What was that?"

00:20:16.850 --> 00:20:21.630
I mean, you couldn't even tell
what it was without explanation.

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:27.930
But to document that
sort of stuff in a way

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:35.040 position:56%
that somebody's words could never
reproduce comes as close as possible

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:38.620
to capturing the feeling of what
it was like to sort of be alive

00:20:38.620 --> 00:20:42.430
at that time and take part in it.

00:20:42.430 --> 00:20:43.730
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Terrific.

00:20:43.730 --> 00:20:46.200
Verna, can we move
to our next section.

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:53.560
And this group photographs
deal with civil disobedience.

00:20:56.510 --> 00:21:00.550
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: Well, you know, I
might say something about Dr. King

00:21:00.550 --> 00:21:06.690
that maybe some of
you know or don't.

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:11.480
But, you know, he died at 39,

00:21:11.480 --> 00:21:20.230
and he traveled 24 million
miles as part of his mission.

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:24.760
Most of that travel had to
do with going out to try

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:29.260
to fund civil rights activities.

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:34.030
He was arrested, I
think, more than 30 times.

00:21:34.030 --> 00:21:36.190
Attacked numerous times.

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:41.210
And he, you know, of course,
led the movement in Birmingham.

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:44.080
That picture of the
hosing is actually --

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:49.170
Lillian Smith, the great southern
writer, told me we were going

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:53.240
to work together on
something that never,

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:54.610
unlike our book, didn't come about.

00:21:54.610 --> 00:22:00.010
But anyway, she said, "Bob,"
she said, "don't pay attention

00:22:00.010 --> 00:22:04.120
to what the whites are doing.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:06.600
They're doing the same stuff."

00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:13.310
She says, "It's the blacks
in the Civil Rights Movement

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:19.620
who are taking their bodies,"
which were chained, and beaten,

00:22:19.620 --> 00:22:23.160
and slaved, "and they're
using their bodies.

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:26.070
They're going to sit down.

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:28.600
They're, you know,
standing up to vote."

00:22:28.600 --> 00:22:33.360
And she said, "Just
watch what they're doing.

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:36.170
That's what's new.

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:42.900
The white people are just,
you know, resisting them."

00:22:42.900 --> 00:22:46.300
And of course, she
also explained to me

00:22:46.300 --> 00:22:50.050
that segregation wasn't
just separating the races.

00:22:50.050 --> 00:22:54.560 position:56%
It was an organized system of terror
to prevent blacks, essentially,

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:58.810
from voting, but from, you
know, enjoying the full equality

00:22:58.810 --> 00:23:03.930
that we fought the Civil War
to, you know, bring about.

00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:06.600
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Can you
tell us what was happening

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:07.900
in this photograph?

00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:09.460
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: Oh, well,
this is in Brooklyn, Ira.

00:23:09.460 --> 00:23:11.460
[laughter]

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:12.760
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: It was there too.

00:23:12.760 --> 00:23:15.590
Some of us didn't know
it, but it was there too.

00:23:15.590 --> 00:23:18.850
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: It's
at a building site.

00:23:18.850 --> 00:23:27.220
And this woman is preventing
a truck from exiting.

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:31.270
There was -- at that time, the
building trades were quite --

00:23:31.270 --> 00:23:35.150
they were very good
jobs, well-paying jobs,

00:23:35.150 --> 00:23:42.150 position:56%
and they didn't have enough black
workers, and so they were protesting

00:23:42.150 --> 00:23:49.440
that this was a state project or
something, building a hospital.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:54.300
And so -- and of course,
why is this woman out there?

00:23:54.300 --> 00:23:56.520
Well, if the men can't get jobs,

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:59.620
they can't be husbands,
they can't be fathers.

00:23:59.620 --> 00:24:05.600
So anyway, they stopped
the trucks at that point.

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:10.350 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: That was a big issue
in New York that a lot of people

00:24:10.350 --> 00:24:14.430 position:56%
who regarded themselves as advocates
for racial justice, like me,

00:24:14.430 --> 00:24:17.730
were not aware of for
a very long time.

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:20.330
I mean, the New York City,

00:24:20.330 --> 00:24:23.360
particularly the construction
building trades,

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:26.710
was a locked down union town.

00:24:26.710 --> 00:24:30.020
You could not have a job
in the building trades

00:24:30.020 --> 00:24:31.810
if you were not a member
of the union.

00:24:31.810 --> 00:24:34.270
And labor unions, because of
the heritage of what happened

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:39.100
in the '30s, labor unions were seen
as an instrument of social justice.

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:43.590
But in New York, they were an
instrument of racial exclusion.

00:24:43.590 --> 00:24:46.550 position:56%
My father was a construction worker,

00:24:46.550 --> 00:24:49.320
and he grew up d during
the Depression.

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:51.470
And I still remember,
as a small boy,

00:24:51.470 --> 00:24:56.290
that he hardly ever worked a
full week, and it was a struggle.

00:24:56.290 --> 00:25:01.370
But the only reason he had a job
was because somebody black didn't,

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:04.550
because they were excluded
from the competition.

00:25:04.550 --> 00:25:07.330
Even though there were
large numbers in New York,

00:25:07.330 --> 00:25:09.550
they couldn't get into the union.

00:25:09.550 --> 00:25:12.790
And if you couldn't get into
the union, you didn't work.

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:16.630
And I remember as a small boy
going to the union hiring hole

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:20.500
with my father and never noticing

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:23.270
that there weren't any
blacks there, ever.

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:24.870 position:56%
And the reason I never noticed it is

00:25:24.870 --> 00:25:26.840
because there weren't
any blacks anywhere.

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:32.190
Not in my school, not in the
stores where my mother shopped.

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:35.970
When I say not in my school, I
don't mean just not teachers.

00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:37.270
Not students.

00:25:37.270 --> 00:25:42.610
You know, New York was a
multiracial, multiethnic place,

00:25:42.610 --> 00:25:47.770
but you lived in neighborhoods
that were entirely singular.

00:25:47.770 --> 00:25:49.860
There were Czech neighborhoods,
and Polish neighborhoods,

00:25:49.860 --> 00:25:51.640
and Irish Catholic neighborhoods.

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:56.820
I lived in a neighborhood where
if you came down from my building

00:25:56.820 --> 00:26:00.170
and walked, you know, as far
as I could walk as a child

00:26:00.170 --> 00:26:03.640
in any direction, you
never saw anybody

00:26:03.640 --> 00:26:08.420
that wasn't white and
Jewish, you know.

00:26:08.420 --> 00:26:13.110
So one of the things that happened
is that not seeing black folks

00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:15.440
in places where they
were being excluded

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:19.080
from with dire consequences,
like the labor union holes,

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:24.090
or the voting lines, was not
unusual, so you didn't notice it.

00:26:24.090 --> 00:26:27.200
And that's why all of that
stuff that we was going

00:26:27.200 --> 00:26:31.250
on in the south was also going on
in the north in different ways,

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:34.970
but in ways in which the people who
supported racial justice movements

00:26:34.970 --> 00:26:39.910
in the south managed to insulate
themselves from in the north.

00:26:39.910 --> 00:26:43.530
And the man who changed
that was Jackie Robinson.

00:26:43.530 --> 00:26:44.830
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: There you go.

00:26:44.830 --> 00:26:46.130
There you go.

00:26:46.130 --> 00:26:48.670
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: Because,
I mean, this was 1947.

00:26:48.670 --> 00:26:51.820
This was what I like to call the
first great civil rights event

00:26:51.820 --> 00:26:54.090
of the post-war era.

00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:58.030
And it was an event -- I was nine
years old, and if you were trying

00:26:58.030 --> 00:26:59.750
to teach me about this
stuff in school,

00:26:59.750 --> 00:27:01.630
I probably would have glazed over.

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:05.470
But the Brooklyn Dodgers were the
most important thing in our lives,

00:27:05.470 --> 00:27:08.490
and all of a sudden, we were
involved in this racial struggle.

00:27:08.490 --> 00:27:10.320 position:56%
And what mattered to us, you know --

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:13.400
I often said if the Yankees
had bought up Jackie Robinson,

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:16.850
I would have been a racist,
because we hated the Yankees.

00:27:16.850 --> 00:27:18.200
[laughter].

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:20.990
And what was important to us was
not the color of a man's skin.

00:27:20.990 --> 00:27:22.710
It was the color of his uniform.

00:27:22.710 --> 00:27:24.010
[laughter].

00:27:24.010 --> 00:27:27.670 position:56%
And but of course, it was impossible
for the Yankees to have bought

00:27:27.670 --> 00:27:30.940
up Jackie Robinson, because
the Yankees were a different --

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:34.040
we all knew that, you know,
if you were a Dodger fan,

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:35.720
you grew up to believe
in social justice.

00:27:35.720 --> 00:27:38.330
If you were a Giants fan,
you were kind of confused.

00:27:38.330 --> 00:27:40.530
But if you were a Yankee
fan, you grew up to believe

00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:42.440
in oil depletion allowances.

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:45.540
And the Yankees were one of
the last teams to hire --

00:27:45.540 --> 00:27:50.550
they didn't hire their first
black player till 1955, you know,

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:53.670
when almost every team
had every black players.

00:27:53.670 --> 00:27:56.590
But the important thing
is that Robinson went

00:27:56.590 --> 00:27:59.120
through all this stuff, that
if you saw that movie 42,

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:03.170
which was a pretty accurate
rendition of that history.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:08.740
You're nine years old,
this is your favorite team,

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:11.600 position:56%
and he was the most exciting player,
and this is your favorite player,

00:28:11.600 --> 00:28:14.370
and they are tearing him up.

00:28:14.370 --> 00:28:21.020
And the way I first learned
about racial exclusion in hotels

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:25.750
and restaurants was because
of hearing on the radio,

00:28:25.750 --> 00:28:28.150
during the broadcast
of the Dodger games,

00:28:28.150 --> 00:28:31.580
that when the Dodgers played
the Cardinals in St. Louis,

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:34.590 position:56%
Jackie Robinson, and Roy Campanella,
and Don Newcombe had to stay

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:38.370
at a different hotel and
eat a different restaurant.

00:28:38.370 --> 00:28:42.390
28:35 And that's how I came to
learn about racial exclusion

00:28:42.390 --> 00:28:45.340
and public accommodation,
and that's why I hated it.

00:28:45.340 --> 00:28:47.760
Nobody taught it to
me in moral terms.

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:50.890
Nobody -- you know, you
just -- this was your guy.

00:28:50.890 --> 00:28:54.240
And it was an extraordinary
thing for --

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:59.200
people wrote later about what
Robinson meant as a role model

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:04.700 position:56%
for black kids, but nobody wrote
for many, many decades what it meant

00:29:04.700 --> 00:29:06.970
as a role model for white kids.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:11.490
On my block, because
Robinson was our favorite,

00:29:11.490 --> 00:29:18.180
we all imitated his batting stance,
his style of running the bases.

00:29:18.180 --> 00:29:20.080
He became a hero to us.

00:29:20.080 --> 00:29:24.530 position:56%
This was something that what I later
called the integration of the soul.

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:28.230
I mean, it was an integration
that was going on psychologically

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:30.820
that we weren't even aware of.

00:29:30.820 --> 00:29:33.790
And I was never aware of it
until I came, decades later,

00:29:33.790 --> 00:29:37.280
to work at the ACLU, where I
discovered a strange thing,

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:38.580
which I first used to joke about,

00:29:38.580 --> 00:29:40.950
and then I realized
was not an accident.

00:29:40.950 --> 00:29:47.630
That was that every male person
who worked at the ACLU who was

00:29:47.630 --> 00:29:50.900
about my age was an old Dodger fan.

00:29:50.900 --> 00:29:52.200
[laughter].

00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:54.770
There were no Yankee
fans at the ACLU.

00:29:54.770 --> 00:29:56.070
[inaudible].

00:29:56.070 --> 00:29:58.660
And that was -- and because one of
the things that happened is, also,

00:29:58.660 --> 00:30:03.250
you went to Ebbets Field, and
Ebbets Field in 1947, '48,

00:30:03.250 --> 00:30:08.110 position:56%
'49 was probably the only integrated
public accommodation in the country,

00:30:08.110 --> 00:30:12.840
because now, suddenly, black
folks came out to see Robinson.

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:15.450
And so I'm 9, 10, 11 years old.

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:17.640
I'm starting to go to
Ebbets Field by myself.

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:20.150
I go to the game, and
I'm sitting next

00:30:20.150 --> 00:30:23.090
to a black guy about, I don't know.

00:30:23.090 --> 00:30:24.390
He was 40.

00:30:24.390 --> 00:30:25.690
He was in undershirt.

00:30:25.690 --> 00:30:27.900
He was drinking beer, you know,
doing what baseball fans do.

00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:31.250 position:56%
And we were on the same side, and
we were rooting for the same things.

00:30:31.250 --> 00:30:33.140
And when somebody did
something good on the Dodgers,

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:35.360
we were slapping each
other and hugging.

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:39.060
This was an experience that a
white boy could not have had

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:42.310
and did not have anywhere
else in this country.

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:45.320
And what it did is it
created a sense of humanity.

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:48.520
These were no longer
people who were others.

00:30:48.520 --> 00:30:51.090
These were people who were us.

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:53.240
And none of this was conscious.

00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:54.650
Nobody talked about it.

00:30:54.650 --> 00:30:56.790
Nobody -- but that's what happened.

00:30:56.790 --> 00:30:59.220
And this is the only place

00:30:59.220 --> 00:31:03.080
where I ever saw black
folks in a normal setting.

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:06.840
I didn't see them in stores, or
in movies, or in voting lines,

00:31:06.840 --> 00:31:10.790
or in union holes, or
in school, no place.

00:31:10.790 --> 00:31:12.340
I saw them at Ebbets Field.

00:31:12.340 --> 00:31:14.690
And it changed the country.

00:31:14.690 --> 00:31:18.380
That's why it was a great civil
rights event before anybody

00:31:18.380 --> 00:31:24.400
recognized it as such, and not
just a great baseball event.

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:28.700
And all of that stuff
that was happening

00:31:28.700 --> 00:31:33.780
in the north was happening not
by law or the Ku Klux Klan.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:37.170
It was happening by
custom, and acceptance,

00:31:37.170 --> 00:31:40.190
and complicity, and blindness.

00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:44.400
But it happened as strongly in the
north as it happened in the south.

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:47.530
And at the beginning of
the Civil Rights Movement,

00:31:47.530 --> 00:31:49.460 position:56%
nobody recognized that in the north.

00:31:49.460 --> 00:31:52.080
And after they were told
about it, they denied it,

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:56.420
and it became a big -- and the
labor union stuff, and the business

00:31:56.420 --> 00:32:01.940
about that woman blocking the
construction was all about that

00:32:01.940 --> 00:32:06.900
in a way that was not
explicit or understood by a lot

00:32:06.900 --> 00:32:09.340
of well-meaning white
folks at the time.

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:10.640
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Wow.

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:13.660
Verna, can you go back to the
photograph of the soda fountain?

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:22.430
What was happening here?

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:24.680
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: Oh, this was in --

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:25.980
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: The
white tower, right?

00:32:25.980 --> 00:32:29.730
&gt;&gt; Bob Adelman: Yeah,
White Castle in the Bronx.

00:32:29.730 --> 00:32:37.220
And CORE was trying to get jobs
for, you know, black workers.

00:32:37.220 --> 00:32:46.550
And there, the pickets
are outside, picketing,

00:32:46.550 --> 00:32:55.190
though sometimes they came in
and sat in at the facility.

00:32:55.190 --> 00:32:59.560
But, you know, people will
often say, "Well, you know what,

00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:01.860
there was already discrimination,

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:06.030
and in the south, there
was segregation."

00:33:06.030 --> 00:33:09.450
But in fact, at certain
points, you know,

00:33:09.450 --> 00:33:16.290
denying somebody a job really means
often denying them a way of life.

00:33:16.290 --> 00:33:23.710
And you know, this is how,
