00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:55.700
and attempts to change laws
and give, you know, equality.

00:43:55.700 --> 00:43:57.000
&gt;&gt; Ira Glasser: Yeah,
and one of the things

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:00.420
that is not well understand
still, I think,

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:03.930
is how infectious these
rights movements were,

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:07.320
that each one became
a model for the other.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:10.010
And this was explicit.

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:14.970
I mean, I remember when gay people
first started coming to the ACLU

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:19.020 position:56%
to ask about lawsuits, when high
school students first started coming

00:44:19.020 --> 00:44:24.370
[inaudible], when prisoners, mental
patients, children in foster care.

00:44:24.370 --> 00:44:27.650
All of these groups that were
somehow outside the protections

00:44:27.650 --> 00:44:29.200
of the Bill of Rights.

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:33.430
The Civil Rights Movement became
a model for, "Well, what about me?

00:44:33.430 --> 00:44:34.730
What about us?

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:36.190
Can we do the same thing?"

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:39.060
There was the disability movement.

00:44:39.060 --> 00:44:43.710
I don't know if I saw
this in a picture of yours

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:45.170
or if I saw it somewhere else,

00:44:45.170 --> 00:44:49.810
but there was this disability
rights demonstration in Syracuse,

00:44:49.810 --> 00:44:52.340
New York in the mid '70s.

00:44:52.340 --> 00:44:58.350
And there was a young person in
a wheelchair with a big poster

00:44:58.350 --> 00:45:03.670 position:56%
that said -- they were demonstrating
against the March of Dimes,

00:45:03.670 --> 00:45:07.150
because the March of Dimes
had become very paternalistic,

00:45:07.150 --> 00:45:11.590
and they had their
grievances, whatever they were.

00:45:11.590 --> 00:45:13.510
And then of course,
there came a time when,

00:45:13.510 --> 00:45:17.390
once polio was virtually conquered,
the March of Dimes became passé,

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:22.940
and people stopped caring about
contributing to disability,

00:45:22.940 --> 00:45:25.830
and they wouldn't contribute
to disability rights movements.

00:45:25.830 --> 00:45:29.990
And this kid had this big sign
that said, "You gave us your dimes.

00:45:29.990 --> 00:45:32.100
Now we want our rights."

00:45:32.100 --> 00:45:34.310
It was a great, you know,

00:45:34.310 --> 00:45:37.440
sort of startled reaction
that everybody had.

00:45:37.440 --> 00:45:40.600
And these movements
all fed on each other.

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:43.850
If you look at the history of
the development of the law,

00:45:43.850 --> 00:45:47.950
and the litigation, and the cases,
and the Bill of Rights applying

00:45:47.950 --> 00:45:50.130
to blacks, and then the Bill
of Rights applying to women,

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:52.550 position:56%
and then the Bill of Rights applying
to prisoners, and then the Bill

00:45:52.550 --> 00:45:54.080
of Rights applying
to mental patients,

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:56.750
and the Bill of Rights applying
to children in foster care.

00:45:56.750 --> 00:46:01.630
Each time those cases came in,
they asked the same question.

00:46:01.630 --> 00:46:03.660
"Well, why doesn't the
Bill of Rights apply to me?

00:46:03.660 --> 00:46:08.600
Why can't a prisoner have the right
to free speech that's involved

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:12.350
in keeping a diary in which he's
critical in the prison ward?

00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:13.650
Why can't," you know.

00:46:13.650 --> 00:46:18.060
And so the issue of the First
Amendment as it applies in prisons.

00:46:18.060 --> 00:46:21.670
And all of these cases
became precedents

00:46:21.670 --> 00:46:22.970
for all these other cases.

00:46:22.970 --> 00:46:25.780
So these movements
were never separated.

00:46:25.780 --> 00:46:27.960 position:56%
There were, to some extent, copycat.

00:46:27.960 --> 00:46:32.330
They were, to some extent, taking
the lessons of one movement

00:46:32.330 --> 00:46:37.060
and applying them to my problem.

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:43.740
And what happened in the '60s,
in a single summary phrase,

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:47.010
is that the Bill of Rights
became alive for people

00:46:47.010 --> 00:46:51.030
to whom it had never applied,
and it happened over and over

00:46:51.030 --> 00:46:54.550
and over again, and it happened
within a pretty brief period

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:58.030
of time, from about 1954,
when Brown against Board

00:46:58.030 --> 00:47:02.920
of Education was decided, to 1973,
when Roe v. Wade was decided.

00:47:02.920 --> 00:47:07.960
Virtually of the rights that we
wake up with every morning and take

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:11.270
for granted were established
as enforceable rights

00:47:11.270 --> 00:47:14.600
for the first time in
that 20-year period.

00:47:14.600 --> 00:47:18.180
And not just by the Supreme
Court, but by those movements,

00:47:18.180 --> 00:47:21.860
which really forced
the issue on everybody.

00:47:23.740 --> 00:47:26.330
Yeah, that's right.

