I would tell them my story.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:09.690 position:56%
And my story was, is that, as I said
earlier, my father took jobs away

00:50:09.690 --> 00:50:12.550
from black construction
workers in New York

00:50:12.550 --> 00:50:17.060
and never knew it,
and I never knew it.

00:50:17.060 --> 00:50:20.590
But I'll tell you what,
he benefited by it.

00:50:20.590 --> 00:50:22.970
I benefited by it.

00:50:22.970 --> 00:50:24.950
And I came to understand
that because,

00:50:24.950 --> 00:50:29.560
on the day before Jackie
Robinson came to the Dodgers,

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:37.290
there were 400 baseball jobs,
25 per team for eight teams.

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:44.260
And on the day he had a job,
one white person didn't.

00:50:44.260 --> 00:50:47.300
And you could say that he took that
job away from the white person,

00:50:47.300 --> 00:50:50.470
but the white person and
never should have had that job

00:50:50.470 --> 00:50:52.870
if there was an open
competition among all the people

00:50:52.870 --> 00:50:56.520
who were excluded for reasons
that had nothing to do with merit

00:50:56.520 --> 00:50:58.630 position:56%
or their ability to perform the job.

00:50:58.630 --> 00:51:01.470
And nobody talked about
women taking jobs away

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:04.970
from men during World War Two, when
they were all over there fighting

00:51:04.970 --> 00:51:09.250
and when our economy and the war
effort was supported by women,

00:51:09.250 --> 00:51:13.480
who after the war, were thought
to be unsuited for the very jobs

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:14.820 position:56%
that they were doing during the war.

00:51:14.820 --> 00:51:18.610
I mean, so the same thing is
sort of always true, you know.

00:51:18.610 --> 00:51:21.300
And what happens with
those kind of questions is

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:24.760
that they play victims off
against each other, you know.

00:51:24.760 --> 00:51:29.010
When there are not enough jobs
to go around, it helps the people

00:51:29.010 --> 00:51:31.730
who have them if whole classes

00:51:31.730 --> 00:51:34.530
of people are excluded
from competing for them.

00:51:34.530 --> 00:51:38.700
And it's always -- I mean,
the reason why poor whites

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:45.500 position:56%
in the south were always supporters
of racial injustice in the south was

00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:48.650
because the blacks were the
only people who were below them,

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:52.300
and their position in
the social and economic

00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:56.280
and political hierarchy was
dependent upon the subjugation

00:51:56.280 --> 00:51:57.580
of black people.

00:51:57.580 --> 00:52:01.130
So they had an interest in
maintaining that subjugation.

00:52:01.130 --> 00:52:07.650
And so the whole issue of taking
jobs away, taking housing away,

00:52:07.650 --> 00:52:11.130
taking all that -- voting
is a perfect example.

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:13.260
If you're going to let blacks
vote, whites aren't going

00:52:13.260 --> 00:52:14.560
to dominate the election.

00:52:14.560 --> 00:52:15.860
If you're going to let --

00:52:15.860 --> 00:52:21.450
I mean, women in this country
couldn't vote till 1920, remember.

00:52:21.450 --> 00:52:23.160
This was the land of the
free and the home of the --

00:52:23.160 --> 00:52:25.850
this was, you know, all men
are created equal, you know.

00:52:25.850 --> 00:52:28.830
Turns out they really
did mean all men,

00:52:28.830 --> 00:52:30.650
and they didn't even mean all men.

00:52:30.650 --> 00:52:31.950
They didn't mean black men.

00:52:31.950 --> 00:52:33.290
They didn't mean American
Indian men.

00:52:33.290 --> 00:52:37.070
They didn't even mean white
men who didn't own property.

00:52:37.070 --> 00:52:42.610
The narrowness of the application
of the rights that we regard today

00:52:42.610 --> 00:52:47.430
as universal, the narrowness of
the groups to which they applied

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:50.580
and the groups who were
excluded and on the outside

00:52:50.580 --> 00:52:55.510
of those protections
is still something

00:52:55.510 --> 00:52:59.440
that most Americans
don't understand.

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:06.730
And we are all -- I mean, my
father was able to buy a home,

00:53:06.730 --> 00:53:11.680
a suburban home, in 1950,
because he had a job

00:53:11.680 --> 00:53:13.710
that black folks couldn't
compete with.

00:53:13.710 --> 00:53:18.070
Then he was able to have that home
in the suburbs because he was able

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:24.540
to get a mortgage that black
folks were excluded from getting.

00:53:24.540 --> 00:53:31.450 position:56%
Then that home became the major form
of wealth for working class people

00:53:31.450 --> 00:53:34.160
when they died and had bequest.

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:38.690
And so people like me, and
then subsequently my children

00:53:38.690 --> 00:53:42.800
and my grandchildren, had
benefits, financial benefits,

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:47.380
along the way that were the direct
result of the fact that my father

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:50.500
in difficult economic times did
not have to compete with blacks.

00:53:50.500 --> 00:53:53.920
Not for a home, not for a
mortgage, not for a job.

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:57.590
And that's how I get to go to
college, and that's how my kids get

00:53:57.590 --> 00:54:01.130 position:56%
to go to college, and that's how I
get a small inheritance from a house

00:54:01.130 --> 00:54:04.290
that other people couldn't own.

00:54:04.290 --> 00:54:08.600
And so when white,
of my kids generation

00:54:08.600 --> 00:54:12.220
and my grandchildren's generation
who don't know any of this.

00:54:12.220 --> 00:54:16.640
Talk about reverse discrimination
and how utterly unaware

00:54:16.640 --> 00:54:20.800
of how they were the
beneficiaries of discrimination.

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:23.600
They say, "But I didn't
discriminate.

00:54:23.600 --> 00:54:24.900
And you didn't discriminate.

00:54:24.900 --> 00:54:28.150
You spent your whole life
fighting against that, Grandpa.

00:54:28.150 --> 00:54:32.330
So why" -- but the fact
that we didn't discriminate,

00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:35.330
the fact that we were
opposed to discrimination,

00:54:35.330 --> 00:54:37.630
did not mean we didn't
benefit by it,

00:54:37.630 --> 00:54:41.650
and that's where the moral
obligation comes from.

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:45.770
And that's really a matter,
as the generations pass on,

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:49.690
you have to find some way to
teach that, because there's no way

00:54:49.690 --> 00:54:52.940
that kids who are ten years
old today could know about it.

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:54.240
